SIMPLE: puff
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Puff
<hw>Puff</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Akin to G. & Sw.
<ets>puff</ets> a blow, Dan. <ets>puf</ets>, D. <ets>pof</ets>; of
imitative origin. Cf. <er>Buffet</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A sudden
and single emission of breath from the mouth; hence, any sudden or short
blast of wind; a slight gust; a whiff.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ To every
<xex>puff</xex> of wind a slave.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Flatman.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Anything light and filled with air. Specifically:
<sd>(a)</sd> A puffball. <sd>(b)</sd> kind of light pastry. <sd>(c)</sd>
A utensil of the toilet for dusting the skin or hair with
powder.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An exaggerated or empty expression of praise,
especially one in a public journal.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Puff adder</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>Any South African viper belonging to <gen>Clotho</gen> and allied
genera. They are exceedingly venomous, and have the power of greatly
distending their bodies when irritated. The common puff adder
(<spn>Vipera arietans</spn>, <it>or</it> <spn>Clotho arietans</spn>) is
the largest species, becoming over four feet long. The plumed puff adder
(<spn>Clotho cornuta</spn>) has a plumelike appendage over each
eye.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>A North American harmless snake
(<spn>Heterodon platyrrhinos</spn>) which has the power of puffing up
its body. Called also <altname>hog-nose snake</altname>,
<altname>flathead</altname>, <altname>spreading adder</altname>, and
<altname>blowing adder</altname>.</cd> -- <col><b>Puff bird</b></col>
<fld>(Zool.)</fld>, <cd>any bird of the genus <gen>Bucco</gen>, or
family <fam>Bucconid⟦ae⟧</fam>. They are small birds, usually with
dull-colored and loose plumage, and have twelve tail feathers. See
<er>Barbet</er> <sd>(b)</sd>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Puff
<hw>Puff</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Puffed</conjf> <pr>(p⟦ucr⟧ft)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Puffing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Akin to G. <ets>puffen</ets> to
pop, buffet, puff, D. <ets>poffen</ets> to pop, <ets>puffen</ets> to
blow, Sw. <ets>puffa</ets> to push, to cuff, Dan. <ets>puffe</ets> to
pop, thump. See <er>Puff</er>, <pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
blow in puffs, or with short and sudden whiffs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To blow, as an expression of scorn; -- with
<xex>at</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>It is really to defy Heaven to <qex>puff</qex> at damnation.</q>
<rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To breathe quick and hard, or with puffs, as after
violent exertion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ass comes back again, <qex>puffing</qex> and blowing, from the
chase.</q> <rj><qau>L' Estrange.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To swell with air; to be dilated or inflated.</def>
<rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To breathe in a swelling, inflated, or pompous
manner; hence, to assume importance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Then came brave Glory <qex>puffing</qex> by.</q>
<rj><qau>Herbert.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Puff
<hw>Puff</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To drive with a puff,
or with puffs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The clearing north will <qex>puff</qex> the clouds away.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To repel with words; to blow at
contemptuously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>puff</qex> the prostitute away.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to swell or dilate; to inflate; to ruffle
with puffs; -- often with <ptcl>up</ptcl>; <as>as, a bladder
<ex>puffed</ex> with air</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The sea <qex>puffed</qex> up with winds.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To inflate with pride, flattery, self-esteem, or the
like; -- often with <ptcl>up</ptcl>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Puffed</qex> up with military success.</q> <rj><qau>Jowett
(Thucyd. )</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To praise with exaggeration; to flatter; to call
public attention to by praises; to praise unduly.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ Puffed
with wonderful skill.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puff</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Puff
<hw>Puff</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Puffed up; vain.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark> <rj><au>Fanshawe.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Puffball</ent>⟦br⟧
